{#- LLM-facing text is English-only: Cyrillic uses roughly 2–3× more tokens per word.
    This Jinja comment is stripped and never sent to the model.
    docs/ARCHITECTURE.md §6.2: tool-spec for route `cli_intent`. -#}
{
  "type": "function",
  "function": {
    "name": "cli_intent",
    "description": "Maze move — EXPLORE the file/system part of the labyrinth. Request shell execution via CLI pipeline (allow/deny/HITL). Use for external effects, live system state, or read-only discovery on the agent host. Discovery (read-only): before creating or editing files, inventory existing code with rg, find, cat, head, ls; git read-only only (git grep, git log, git show) — never git commit/push/reset without explicit user request. Shell chains allowed: use &&, ;, or | in argv (e.g. [\"rg\", \"-l\", \"Foo\", \"path\", \"|\", \"head\", \"-n\", \"20\"]) or [\"sh\", \"-c\", \"rg -l Foo path | head -n 20\"] — every segment must use allowlisted binaries; $( and backticks are denied. Safety: non-interactive flags; limit output; no destructive commands without explicit user request; no secrets in argv.\n\nWhen NOT to use: a fact retrievable from the knowledge graph → memory_query first; broad multi-step repo survey → subagent_intent with an inventory-only task. Cost/latency: chained allowlisted commands auto-run; unknown binaries in a chain may require HITL.\n\nargv[0] is an OS binary from the allowlist (ls, cat, rg, find, head, git, python3, …), NEVER the name of an FSM route. Routes — memory_query, reflect, formal_reason, response_append, response_edit, response_observe, response_finalize, thread_memory, global_memory, subagent_intent, tasks_upsert — are separate tools you call directly, not shell commands. To query the knowledge/memory graph call the memory_query tool (not cli_intent ['memory_query', …]). A cli_intent whose command is a route name is bounced back as an observation telling you to call the real tool, wasting a hop.\n\nDiscovery examples: [\"rg\", \"-l\", \"EmailBridge\", \"ansible/roles/threlium/files/scripts/threlium/bridges\"], [\"rg\", \"-n\", \"pattern\", \"path\", \"|\", \"head\", \"-n\", \"30\"], [\"find\", \"path\", \"-name\", \"*bridge*\"]. Implementation example: [\"pip\", \"install\", \"--no-input\", \"ruff\"].",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "argv": {
          "type": "array",
          "items": {"type": "string", "minLength": 1, "maxLength": 4000},
          "minItems": 1,
          "maxItems": 64,
          "description": "Command and arguments as argv array; use separate tokens for shell operators (&&, |, ;). For a full shell line use [\"sh\", \"-c\", \"…\"]. argv[0] is the binary name for simple commands."
        },
        "cwd": {
          "type": "string",
          "maxLength": 4000,
          "description": "Working directory for execution (optional)."
        },
        "reasoning": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 2000,
          "description": "Why this command is needed — short text for logs and HITL confirmation."
        }
      },
      "required": ["argv", "reasoning"],
      "additionalProperties": false
    }
  }
}
